---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import SectionHeader from '../../components/SectionHeader.astro';
import PullQuote from '../../components/PullQuote.astro';
import Annotation from '../../components/Annotation.astro';
import Sample from '../../components/Sample.astro';
---
<Base title="Restraint Is Active Work" section={3}>
  <article class="prose">

    <SectionHeader
      n={3}
      title="Restraint Is Active Work"
      meta="~600 words · 1 interactive sample"
    />

    <p>
      The hardest design review conversation isn't "should we add this?" It's
      "should we remove this?" Adding features has a clear story: user asked
      for it, we built it, done. Removing a feature requires arguing that
      absence is better than presence — which means arguing that users are
      wrong about what they want, which is an uncomfortable position to
      defend in a room full of stakeholders.
    </p>

    <p>
      And yet. The interfaces that age best — the ones people describe as
      timeless, as calm, as trustworthy — are almost universally the ones
      where something was taken away. Not because minimalism is a style, but
      because every persistent visual element is a small, continuous tax
      levied against the reader's focus. The tax is real even when the element
      is invisible. The brain processes the page, finds nothing to act on,
      and returns to the task. That return costs something.
    </p>

    <PullQuote>
      Minimalism isn't the absence of decisions — it's the hardest kind.
      The work is invisible precisely because so much effort went into
      removing things.
    </PullQuote>

    <h2>Controls that earn their appearance</h2>

    <p>
      The principle isn't "never show controls." It's "show controls when
      they're genuinely relevant, and not before." The specific mechanism
      is hover-reveal with a gentle fade: controls live at zero opacity,
      and transition to full opacity when the user demonstrates intent
      by hovering over the content they apply to.
    </p>

    <p>
      This pattern works because it collapses the temporal gap between
      "I might want this control" and "I can see this control." Controls
      that are always visible optimize for the second case while creating
      constant overhead for the first. Controls that appear on hover serve
      both cases while keeping the resting state clean.
    </p>

    <Sample label="Interactive sample — hover to reveal controls">
      <div style="font-family: 'Lora', Georgia, serif;">
        <div style="font-size: 12px; font-family: system-ui, sans-serif; color: #a08060; margin-bottom: 16px; letter-spacing: 0.03em;">
          Hover over the response block below.
        </div>

        <div
          style="background: #f7f0e6; border-radius: 8px; padding: 16px 20px; position: relative; cursor: default;"
          onmouseenter="this.querySelector('.s3-controls').style.opacity='1'"
          onmouseleave="this.querySelector('.s3-controls').style.opacity='0'"
        >
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.8; color: #4a3728; margin: 0;">
            The interface that earns its invisibility leaves no seam between
            intention and execution. You think the thought — and it's already there.
          </p>

          <!-- Hidden controls -->
          <div
            class="s3-controls"
            style="
              position: absolute;
              top: 10px;
              right: 10px;
              display: flex;
              gap: 6px;
              opacity: 0;
              transition: opacity 120ms cubic-bezier(.4,0,.2,1);
            "
          >
            <button style="background: #fdf8f2; border: 0.5px solid #e4d9cc; border-radius: 6px; padding: 5px 10px; font-size: 11px; font-family: system-ui, sans-serif; color: #7a5535; cursor: pointer; letter-spacing: 0.04em;">Copy</button>
            <button style="background: #fdf8f2; border: 0.5px solid #e4d9cc; border-radius: 6px; padding: 5px 10px; font-size: 11px; font-family: system-ui, sans-serif; color: #7a5535; cursor: pointer; letter-spacing: 0.04em;">↻ Retry</button>
            <button style="background: #fdf8f2; border: 0.5px solid #e4d9cc; border-radius: 6px; padding: 5px 10px; font-size: 11px; font-family: system-ui, sans-serif; color: #7a5535; cursor: pointer; letter-spacing: 0.04em;">✕</button>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div style="margin-top: 10px; font-size: 11px; font-family: system-ui, sans-serif; color: #c8ad94; letter-spacing: 0.05em; text-transform: uppercase;">
          Controls at rest: 0 visible elements competing for attention
        </div>
      </div>
    </Sample>

    <p>
      The key implementation detail: the transition duration is
      <code>--dur-fast: 120ms</code> — fast enough that the appearance feels
      responsive rather than delayed, slow enough that it doesn't feel like a
      flash. The reveal is barely perceivable as an animation. It's just
      <em>there</em>, in a way that feels inevitable rather than triggered.
    </p>

    <Annotation label="The real cost">
      Hover-reveal has a drawback on touch devices where hover states don't
      exist. On mobile, these controls need a different trigger — typically
      a tap on the content block. This is not a reason to abandon the pattern.
      It's a reason to design two interaction modes instead of one, and
      to accept that the desktop experience can be cleaner because the
      interaction vocabulary is richer.
    </Annotation>

    <p>
      Restraint isn't a feeling. It's a practice that requires constant
      re-application. Features accrete. Reasonable additions compound into
      unreasonable density. The work of keeping an interface clean is active,
      never finished, and mostly invisible to everyone but the people doing it.
      That invisibility is the point.
    </p>

  </article>
</Base>
